To find the symmetric difference (A x B) ∆ (B x A), we first need to find the Cartesian products A x B and B x A.

A x B = {(1,2), (1,3), (1,4), (2,2), (2,3), (2,4), (3,2), (3,3), (3,4)}
B x A = {(2,1), (2,2), (2,3), (3,1), (3,2), (3,3), (4,1), (4,2), (4,3)}

Now, we find the symmetric difference by taking the elements that are in either (A x B) or (B x A), but not in both.

(A x B) ∆ (B x A) = {(1,2), (1,3), (1,4), (2,1), (3,1), (4,1), (4,2), (4,3)}

So, the set (A x B) ∆ (B x A) is {(1,2), (1,3), (1,4), (2,1), (3,1), (4,1), (4,2), (4,3)}.
